issue(id="0009" status="review")
  title Extract reusable clean/dirty modules with boundary-explicit naming
  user-story
    as-a scrubs maintainer extracting reusable guest behavior
    i-want guest extensions split into clearly named clean and dirty modules with a sharp boundary between reusable capability and project policy
    so-that we can reuse tooling confidently, review trust-boundary intent quickly, and keep project-specific concerns inside project guest files rather than inside shared modules
  premise.
    Scrubs currently has guest-extension points that can carry reusable logic,
    but the shape is still too close to ad hoc shims. That makes it too easy
    for a file to mix together trust-boundary meaning, host-specific bootstrap
    concerns, and project-local policy without making those categories obvious
    to the next reader.

    This issue is about extracting reusable modules as first-class building
    blocks and naming them so their intent is visible immediately. Reusable
    modules should use names such as `clean-gcloud.nix`,
    `clean-docker.nix`, `dirty-gcloud-build.nix`, or
    `dirty-postgres-build.nix`, where the prefix tells the reader which space
    the module serves.

    A clean module is a ready-to-use cleanspace capability: it includes the
    nixpkg intended to run in cleanspace and the configuration required for
    that tool. If a tool does not need accompanying configuration, it does not
    need a dedicated module and can remain just a package choice at the project
    level.

    A dirty module is not a dirty runtime application bundle. It is a reusable
    module that installs the cleanspace foundations required to build software
    that will live in dirtyspace. Its job is to provide build-time support,
    not to smuggle project policy or project-owned runtime concerns into shared
    scrubs base.

    Reusable modules should stay neutral and should not refer to specific
    projects. Any project-specific wiring, enablement, or policy belongs in
    the relevant project `guest.nix` file, which can compose the reusable
    clean and dirty modules it needs.
  acceptance-criteria
    criterion Scrubs has a documented reusable-module model that distinguishes shared clean modules, shared dirty modules, and project-specific `guest.nix` concerns.
    criterion Reusable modules use boundary-explicit names such as `clean-...` and `dirty-...`, so the filename and intent immediately communicate which space the module serves.
    criterion The definition of a clean module is documented: it packages a cleanspace tool together with any configuration needed to use that tool in cleanspace, and modules are not introduced for tools that need no configuration.
    criterion The definition of a dirty module is documented: it provides the cleanspace foundations needed to build software that will live in dirtyspace, rather than bundling project-specific dirty runtime behavior.
    criterion The resulting module layout and examples make it clear that reusable modules must not refer to particular projects, and that project-specific behavior belongs in the project's `guest.nix`.
    criterion At least one example composition shows a project `guest.nix` consuming reusable clean and/or dirty modules without moving project policy into the shared modules themselves.
  review-items
    item(status="open").
      Decide which existing guest customizations should graduate into reusable
      `clean-*` or `dirty-*` modules first, and which ones should remain in
      project `guest.nix` because they encode project-specific policy.
    item(status="open").
      Decide whether modules that only add a package and no configuration
      should be prohibited outright or merely discouraged in documentation and
      review.
    item(status="open").
      Make sure the naming scheme continues to optimize for boundary
      readability and that dirty modules are consistently described as
      cleanspace build-tooling for dirtyspace outputs, not as generic dirty
      app bundles.
